      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nAmong the characteristics of our species, *Homo sapiens*, is the ability to walk and perform manual tasks. These characteristics did not arise from nothing; they are changes that occurred over millions of years and reached us thanks to DNA and different speciation processes — the process by which new species emerge from existing ones (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nGiven this scenario, let us reflect on the following:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b2067355-8f41-470b-a270-1de259627fc2",
                     "text": "National Geographics",
                     "page": "Speciation",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "585d2d43-6335-4bc3-b5b2-17f50a60a47a",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Homo sapiens",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: I am the beginning...</b><br /><br />Given this initial explanation, which species would have been the first to manufacture manual tools?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_habilis",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Working with Hands\n\nOur species is “new,” with the first individuals appearing in the world between <htdate0> and <htdate1> (<htcite0>; <htcite1>; <htcite2>). However, fossils of the genus *Homo* (**Figure 1**) associated with tools are much older, dating back millions of years.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "75d196c9-1c1e-4106-bef5-ce8558d00d31",
                     "text": "Tattersall, I., & Schwartz, J. H.",
                     "page": "pp. 82",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "6830dfc3-a5eb-42b5-bccd-1453014454e7",
                     "text": "Dorey, Fran",
                     "page": "Homo sapiens",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2020",
                        "month": "10",
                        "day": "20"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "585d2d43-6335-4bc3-b5b2-17f50a60a47a",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Homo sapiens",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2026",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "-302000",
                     "month": "",
                     "day": ""
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "-152000",
                     "month": "",
                     "day": ""
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgHabilis\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgHabilis', '0%')\" src=\"images/DonsMaps/img_6652habilissm.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" style=\"width: 30%;\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Reconstruction of the <i>Homo habilis</i>. © Don Hitchcock. Original at the <i>Vienna Natural History Museum</i> (<htcite0>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "e4e24b02-9e06-479a-8f5e-33c6576e79eb",
                     "text": "Hitchcock, Don",
                     "page": "Homo habilis",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2013",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "However, when comparing this skull with a human skull (**Figure 2**), we realize that we are not exactly the same, although we share some similarities.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"imgHS\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('imgHS', '0%')\" src=\"images/MexicoCityMuseo/HomoSapiens.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 2</b>:  Poster of the human skeleton describing <i>Homo sapiens</i>. At the Museu Nacional de Antrologia in Mexico (<htcite0>).</p>",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "0be2ea18-ab78-4cb1-b3be-1ff0ba4ade95",
                     "text": "Museo Nacional de Antropologia",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "As skeletons are the result of the DNA — represented in **Figure 3** — of each living being (<htcite0>), we conclude that the species shown in **Figure 1** cannot be the same as ours, despite already possessing the ability to use hands to create tools.\n\nOver the years and with the conduct of new studies, scientists concluded that the first Homo to successfully create hand tools lived between <htdate0> and <htdate1> and was named *Homo habilis* (<htcite1>; <htcite2>; <htcite3>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "24e35656-4e60-46b9-a4c4-08db2623336e",
                     "text": "Pray, Leslie A.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2008",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "c4c6c745-58d7-4665-8a29-13943c6aa52b",
                     "text": "Spoor, F., Gunz, P., Neubauer, S. et al.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2015",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a27bf40a-6cf8-4c9a-8b53-efcd80864c83",
                     "text": "Dorey, Fran.",
                     "page": "Homo habilis",
                     "date_time": {
